<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-11-05T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-11-05T06:00:00-05:00" n="240" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d240">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/14295: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-11-05T11:00:00+00:00">November 5, 1938—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 5—8:44 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1289. My 1280, November 3, 4 p.m. I have just talked with Cadogan. Last
                            night the Foreign Office sent word to Craigie to see Grew, get the gist
                            of his instructions and make similar representations. Craigie will
                            follow Grew’s lead as to whether they should be made in writing or
                            orally. They have also advised the French that they have so instructed
                            their Ambassador.</p>
                        <p>Copy by mail to Paris.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>